<TEXT>
more tourists than ever are flooding paris 
storming museums mobbing hotels and crowding cafes to kick off 
celebrations marking the french revolution bicentennial 
even though events are just beginning the paris tourism office 
says the capital already has 20 percent more visitors than at this 
time in 1988 
and nationwide officials expect to break last years record of 
38 million visitors 
there are going to be a lot of people in france said xavier 
beguin billecocq a tourism official with the maison de la france 
this year we expect an increase of about 15 percent 
largescale bicentennial events will begin in may but plenty of 
visitors are already in town 
nathalie paul a spokeswoman at the paris tourism office said 
hotel rooms were filling up fast 
we couldnt get into the louvre yesterday the line was 
incredible said judith goldberg of new york city she waited in 
line with hundreds of others outside the musee dorsay the paris 
showcase for 19th century art 
as many as 50000 tourists and parisians have crowded the louvre 
daily since the museums new pyramid entrance opened on march 29 
the louvre renovations were scheduled to be completed in time for 
bicentennial celebrations 
but besides visiting the louvre a museum since the early years 
of the revolution and a few small exhibitions tourists have few 
bicentennial events to attend until next month 
on may 4 the procession that opened the estates general will be 
recreated in versailles two hundred years ago the first second 
and third estates representatives of the nobility clergy and 
commoners met to express the grievances that set the revolution 
in motion 
from may 5 to nov 11 paris tourists can visit a minitheme 
park being set up in the elegant tuileries gardens between the 
louvre and the place de la concorde 
organizers expect at least 35 million people to pay the 
equivalent of three dollars to visit the park which includes two 
small cinemas an exhibition hall a theater souvenir stands two 
cafes and six bars 
two 118foot towers of liberty will mark the recreation area 
and 32 actors in period costume will perform or wander among the 
tourists portraying revolutionary figures 
the maison de la france has counted 6000 bicentennial events 
nationwide from dances and fireworks to arcane academic seminars 
and published a list of 200 considered likely to interest tourists 
the eiffel tower built for the revolutions centennial 
celebrations marks its own 100th birthday this year with special 
festivities on june 1718 
a special us homage to the revolution is scheduled july 8 
with bands from each of the 50 states parading through paris that 
evening the american waterways wind orchestra will play from a 
barge in the seine river to a crowd before city hall 
the lucky few including president bush will attend the july 13 
opening night of the new bastille opera the theater is being built 
near where the bastille was seized on july 14 1789 the most 
memorable event of the confused and turbulent revolutionary years 
musicians will play until dawn in what is being described as the 
worlds biggest ball 
bush president francois mitterrand and the leaders of britain 
west germany japan italy and canada will hold the annual 
sevennation economic summit in paris from july 1416 meetings 
will be interspersed with bicentennial parades fireworks and the 
like 
while paris hosts the largest number of revolutionary 
commemorations the provinces are not left out among the 
highlights will be an assembly of tall ships from july 916 in 
rouen and a gathering of 987 hotair balloons near the small 
village of gouin in eastern france from july 26 to aug 6 
</TEXT>
