<TEXT>
vietnams 10year military occupation 
of cambodia has proved a costly adventure that deprived the 
vietnamese of international support they desperately needed to 
rebuild after years of conflict with the united states 
vietnam announced wednesday it would withdraw its remaining 
5000070000 troops from cambodia by sept 30 
a complete withdrawal without a political settlement would be 
strikingly similar to the soviet pullout from afghanistan or the 
american departure from vietnam 
in each case foreign military intervention fell short of the 
goal of defeating insurgents and guaranteeing a stable friendly 
regime vietnam faces the prospect of seeing the very group it 
sought to defeat the communist khmer rouge reemerge in power 
but the cost of maintaining the occupation has proven too high 
the united states has refused to discuss establishing diplomatic 
relations with hanoi until the cambodian issue is resolved that 
stand has blocked aid vietnams government has begun to seek to 
rebuild its nation 
in june vietnam acknowledged that 25000 of its troops had been 
killed in cambodia and 30000 others had died in border clashes 
before the 1978 invasion 
the occupation also has cost vietnam a chance to expand trade 
ties with noncommunist southeast asian nations 
vietnam launched its invasion on christmas day 1978 three years 
after hanois forces toppled the usbacked south vietnamese 
government in saigon now ho chi minh city 
the vietnamese moved into cambodia to oust the brutal 
administration of the khmer rouge which had killed hundreds of 
thousands of cambodians in a campaign to reshape agriculture and 
society 
by january 1979 vietnamese troops had driven the khmer rouge to 
the thai border and installed heng samrin in power in phnom penh 
but the vietnamese found like the soviets in afghanistan and 
the americans in vietnam that it is easier to invade than depart 
in february 1979 china launched a brief but bloody border war 
to teach vietnam a lesson vietnam inflicted heavy losses on 
chinese forces but the conflict strained vietnamese resources and 
brought china into the cambodian conflict as a source of military 
and diplomatic support for the antivietnamese resistance 
on june 22 1982 the khmer rouge and guerrillas loyal to prince 
norodom sihanouk the former cambodian monarch and to former 
premier son sann announced a resistance coalition that group 
eventually claimed the countrys seat in the united nations 
by then the occupation was weighing heavily on vietnams 
devastated economy finally last june deputy premier vo van kiet 
said the economy faced alarmingly complicated changes 
including famine in the north and runaway inflation 
grain production in 1987 fell from 182 million tons to 176 
million inflation was estimated at nearly 1000 percent and 
unemployment at about 20 percent 
faced with the mounting pressures the vietnamese communist 
politburo met in september to discuss foreign policy in the 
postcambodian period 
sources said the politburo decided to reduce vietnams 
dependence on the soviet union and seek closer ties to the west and 
the prowestern governments of the association of southeast asian 
nations 
the plan however hinged on ending the cambodian adventure 
vietnam withdrew its command staff in june transferring 
responsibility for running the war to the cambodians the soviets 
and americans made similar moves in phasing out their troops in 
afghanistan and south vietnam 
a series of diplomatic moves led to inconclusive peace talks 
between sihanouk and premier hun sen of the vietnamesebacked 
cambodian government 
the future role of the khmer rouge has been the major obstacle 
to a political settlement both vietnam and the united states have 
strongly opposed a khmer rouge return to power 
western diplomats say fighting inside cambodia declined last 
year to its lowest level since the vietnamese invasion but the 
diplomats believe the khmer rouge has been trying to avoid clashes 
and build up arsenals for a showdown after the vietnamese leave 
the khmer rouge denies any intention to seize power 
however the khmer rouge is believed to be the strongest of the 
three groups in the coalition led by sihanouk western estimates 
place the number of khmer rouge guerrillas at 30000 to 40000 
compared with 13000 for the noncommunist khmer peoples national 
liberation armed forces and 19000 for sihanouks forces 
if the conflict comes to a military head the 30000 to 40000 
government forces may be unable to prevail bereft of vietnamese 
help 
