three teams of american experts will travel to 
hanoi later this week for 2 weeks of investigative work searching 
for us servicemen missing from the vietnam war the pentagon said 
monday 
in addition the vietnamese government has informed the united 
states it intends to repatriate 21 remains which may be those of 
americans on april 27 the pentagon said in a statement 
the investigative teams will arrive in hanoi on wednesday for 
what will be the fifth such joint mission working with vietnamese 
officials in the field 
the three teams two comprised of investigators and one 
consisting of forensic scientists have been told they can remain 
in the country until april 30 making this the longest such mission 
ever the pentagon added 
previous usvietnamese field missions were limited to 10 days 
each 
the teams concentrate their efforts primarily on investigating 
geographic areas near the last known position of socalled 
discrepancy cases a discrepancy case is one in which the us 
government has reason to believe an american serviceman survived an 
airplane crash or hostile fire 
the joint teams also attempt to investigate livesighting 
reports and other claims about the fate of missing servicemen 
the pentagon said the three teams participating in this months 
work would consist of a total of 10 individuals a separate team of 
americans will fly to hanoi on april 27 to take possession of the 
remains that vietnam has said it will turn over then 
according to the pentagon there are still 2370 american 
servicemen missing from the vietnam war including 1736 in either 
north or south vietnam in addition 545 are listed as missing in 
laos 83 in cambodia and six in china 
the pentagon said most of the investigative work planned this 
month would be concentrated in what used to be south vietnam in 
and around the area of danang 
