<TEXT>
two agriculture department scientists said 
today that a natural yeast found in the stomach of a beetle can 
neutralize deadly farm chemicals and natural toxins that sometimes 
are found in the nations food supply 
entomologists patrick f dowd and samuel k shen of the 
departments agricultural research service said that if the 
preliminary tests are borne out in further experiments the yeast 
could be used to remove potentially harmful toxins from livestock 
feed and to clean up the environment 
although were not yet sure of its full range of detoxifying 
ability the implication we see here is for the environmental 
cleanup situations like toxic waste dumps shen said 
if the yeast can be developed properly it could be 
massproduced to detoxify a wide variety of plant and chemical 
toxins in the environment he said in a report issued here by the 
usda agency 
shen spoke monday at a meeting of the american chemical society 
in dallas texas he and dowd along with geneticist nancy j 
alexander are working on the project at the agencys northern 
regional research center in peoria ill 
the yeast is found naturally in the stomach of the cigarette 
beetle a pest of stored tobacco spices and other products the 
yeast provides the insect with vitamins and nutrients and it 
neutralizes certain toxins this enables the insect to feed on a 
wider range of plant materials 
in laboratory tests the researchers found that the yeasts 
enzymes acted on a variety of compounds including the insecticides 
parathion and carbaryl phytic acid which can make some seed meals 
unfit as livestock feed and a precursor of aflatoxin a fungal 
toxin suspected of being carcinogenic 
the scientists plan to text the yeast against aflatoxin itself 
some of last years droughtdamaged corn crop has had high levels 
of aflatoxin a naturally occuring carcinogen 
a number of microorganisms are already used to a limited extent 
to clean water systems and soil shen said but unlike those the 
yeast could be used for multiple cleanup tasks 
dowd shens colleague said that one of the limitations of the 
yeast is that it is a slowgrowing microorganism 
to successfully produce this thing we need to find a 
fastergrowing strain or a way to genetically transfer its 
detoxifying ability to a fastergrowing yeast dowd said 
</TEXT>
