<TEXT>
the bush administration tried monday to 
squelch an effort by members of the house banking committee to 
weaken the administrations savings and loan reform plan by 
diluting a proposal to toughen capital standards 
a senior treasury department official briefing reporters on the 
condition of anonymity said the committees proposed capital rule 
has the cosmetic appearance of going in the right direction but 
would undermine the effectiveness of the capital discipline 
in reply a committee aide also speaking on the condition of 
anonymity said the proposal is in some ways tougher although a 
greater number of solvent sampls would be able to meet it 
the aide said a bipartisan majority of the committee supports 
the compromise worked out by staff members in an allday session 
on saturday 
capital represents the interest of an institutions owners the 
more money the owners have at risk before federal deposit insurance 
kicks in the less likely the owners are to make speculative loans 
a central point in president bushs sampl package calls for 
increasing capital standards from 3 percent of assets currently to 
6 percent by june 1991 
the committee aide said the compromise supported by the federal 
deposit insurance corp and the federal home loan bank board would 
move up the deadline to june 1990 but it would more broadly define 
what counts as capital 
the treasury official expressed concern that the proposal would 
allow a return to the bad old days of phantom capital and 
capital pinned on lax regulatory accounting principles 
the part of it that is most disturbing to us is the definition 
of what constitutes capital the official said 
rep jim leach riowa in a luncheon speech to the independent 
bankers association of america said he opposed the committee 
compromise which he said was advocated by reps frank annunzio 
dill and doug barnard dga because it would have the effect 
of lowering the capital standard to 15 percent 
the irony is that the federal home loan bank boards current 
standards would be undercut dramatically he told reporters 
outside the meeting 
there is a great deal of pressure on the committee to be more 
flexible which means accommodating to the industry on capital 
standards he said my own view is that every time you weaken 
the standards you have the effect of weakening the commitment to 
never again 
at the treasury briefing the official said the department would 
support one element of the house proposal a laxer standard for 
residential mortgages requiring half as much capital backing as 
required for other types of loans 
i think the administration knows that theyre going to 
probably have to compromise a bit with congress my hope is that 
congress isnt too weak in what it tries to push down the 
administrations throat leach said 
the house banking subcommittee on financial institutions which 
includes 47 of the full committees 51 members is expected to take 
up capital rules at its second public session on the sampl bill 
scheduled tuesday 
in another development four consumer and community groups 
circulated a letter monday to committee members threatening to 
oppose the sampl legislation unless it contains amendments 
discouraging institutions from discrimination based on sex and race 
and encouraging lending for housing for low and moderateincome 
people 
we will oppose this legislation unless all these are 
responsibly addressed in the bill leaders of the four groups 
wrote remember the public is paying a price tag of more than 
200 billion and therefore must be assured that it will never 
again have to sign a blank check 
the groups are the consumers union consumer federation of 
america association of community organizations for reform now 
acorn and the center for community change 
