charges monday in a test of a state law legally absolving parents 
when religious beliefs prohibit medical care 
nine potential jurors were excused in the trial of william 
hermanson 42 and his 38yearold wife christine on charges of 
thirddegree murder and child abuse in the death 2 years ago of 
their daughter amy 
if convicted the hermansons face three to seven years in prison 
state circuit judge steven dakan took under consideration a 
defense motion to move the trial out of sarasota county on grounds 
of excessive pretrial publicity he said he wanted to see if a fair 
and impartial panel could be chosen in the hermansons hometown 
before ruling 
jurors will be asked to weigh legal and moral questions about 
the balance between religious freedom and childrens rights 
the case challenges a 1975 law absolving parents of abuse or 
neglect charges when they deny their children medical care because 
of deep religious beliefs 
defense attorney thomas dart said the law excludes people like 
the hermansons from criminal charges but prosecutors say the law 
should not shield parents who let their children die 
the hermansons refused a plea bargain under which they would 
have served 15 years probation in return for pleading guilty or no 
contest for a chance to have their case heard by jury 
hermanson worked as a bank vice president and his wife ran a 
fine arts academy they have another child eric 11 
a cornerstone of christian science doctrine is the reliance on 
prayer instead of medicine to care for the ill in difficult cases 
they may seek help from practitioners senior church members 
with expertise in spiritual healing however individuals may seek 
medical assistance without fear of church sanctions 
amy became ill in september 1986 and the hermansons called on 
two such practitioners authorities said she died sept 30 after 
the girl died a medical examiner concluded that medical treatment 
probably could have saved her 
