awarded the custody of her embryos for her exclusive use 
the davises acknowledge that the case is an unusual one 
incorporating medical technology personal rights and ethics and 
that there apparently are no previous court cases like it 
many invitro fertilization clinics require couples to sign 
written agreements regarding the fate of their frozen embryos in 
the event of the man and womans death or divorce however medical 
officials have conceded its hard to draft consent forms that 
include every possible scenario for embryos 
the davises said they were not asked to sign such a paper 
