<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission said 
monday that it has charged the nations largest dealer in penny 
stocks stuartjames co of denver with violating securities laws 
and using deceptive telephone sales practices 
penny stocks typically sell for less than 3 a share some are 
issued by legitimate companies but many are not and the firms 
selling them have come under fire from consumer groups and 
regulators 
the sec in a civil complaint said stuartjames 
excessively marked up prices from 38 percent to 200 percent 
during the first day of trading of two securities it underwrote 
umb equities inc and find svp inc 
falsely and misleadingly in telephone sales pitches predicted 
percentages of return from lowprice speculative investments 
discouraged customrs from selling penny stocks unless another 
customer could be found to purchase the security 
supported the prices of penny stocks by requiring purchasers of 
new issues to either to agree to sell the stock or buy additional 
stock once trading started 
also charged in the complaint were c james padgett and stuart 
graff the principal owners of the firm two current or former 
regional vice presidents and seven current or former branch office 
managers 
marc geman executive vice president of the firm said the 
stocks that were allegedly excessively marked up were sold at the 
lowest offering price on the overthecounter nasdaq system and 
purchased at the highest offering price he also said that the 
companys manual for telephone salespersons specifically forbids 
predicting returns on investments 
stuartjames has 50 offices in 22 states employing 1300 
registered representatives 
the sec in february proposed new rules cracking down on 
highpressure telephone tactics used by penny stock brokers last 
october sec chairman david s ruder established a task force on 
penny stock manipulation 
according to the agencys staff about 325 firms sell penny 
stock up from 55 a few years ago 
