in the soviet union alcoholics undergo compulsory 
hospitalization for as long as six months and are forced to spend 
up to two years in institutions reserved for those who cannot be 
cured by the hospitals 
the fact that it aa is one recovering alcoholic helping 
another one introduces a whole new experience of trust and honesty 
and mutual dependency which the soviet people are not familiar 
with canty said 
mrs dukakis was on hand at kennedy international airport to 
greet the soviet visitors and their translator helen kuzmicheva 
who runs the sovietus alcoholism center in moscow a 
westernstyle outpatient clinic that opened april 3 
mrs dukakis then accompanied them for a quick burger and shake 
at a fast food restaurant in midtown before going to the hospital 
dr marc galanter the director of the division of alcohol and 
drug abuse at bellevue said the soviets seemed to be favorably 
impressed with the hospital 
i think they would have to go a ways in moscow to equal the 
setup here he added 
during their twoweek visit the soviets will also visit the 
world headquarters of alcoholics anonymous in new york attend open 
aa meetings and visit chit chat farms an alcoholism rehabilitation 
center in warnersville pa 
</TEXT>
