<TEXT>
the devil doesnt get his due in temptation 
vaclav havels reworking of the faust legend but then neither does 
the audience 
thats surprising considering the play by czechoslovakias 
leading playwright now in prison for dissident activities has 
been directed by a fellow czech jiri zizka the director with his 
wife blanka runs the highly regarded wilma theater in 
philadelphia where temptation will go after its new york run 
but you cant find the play because of zizkas elaborate and 
selfconscious staging that suffocates the drama and the actors in 
it as well much of temptation which opened over the weekend 
at the new york shakespeare festival public theater is set in a 
science laboratory engaged in what seems to be some kind of 
sinister work the setting allows zizka and set designer jerry rojo 
to fill the stage with hightech scenery accented by slide 
projections smoke screens and weird sound effects 
they are the same devices zizka used several seasons ago in his 
version of george orwells 1984 done at the joyce theater but 
orwells novel of a harrowing future adapted well to zizkas 
stagey devices 
here they seem to overwhelm the actors including such fine 
performers as david strathairn who plays the faust prototype dr 
henry foustka and bill moor as the mincing master of the science 
institute 
foustka dabbles in black magic and his sorcery conjures up a 
mysterious stranger who sounds like laurence olivier and dresses 
like a bowery panhandler is the man a representative of the devil 
or the repressive government that runs the laboratory or are they 
one and the same 
havels conclusion is surprisingly obvious it just takes him a 
long time 10 scenes spread over more than 2 hours to get 
there in between there are foustkas dalliances with several 
women in the lab including a young secretary who is a counterpart 
to fausts doomed margaret shes played here with remarkable 
sympathy by katherine hiler 
havels polemics get more of a workout in foustkas verbal 
sparring with that shabbily dressed stranger some of their 
arguments crackle displaying the passion havel obviously has for 
the free exchange of ideas but in the end their conversations are 
overshadowed by zizkas theatrical tricks making the battle for 
foustkas soul not a very interesting war 
