a former police officer whose acquittal in the 
beating death of a black man led to race riots in 1980 was arrested 
along with a federal agent on drug charges authorities said monday 
the former officer alex marrero 34 and federal drug agent 
jorge villar 44 were charged with conspiring to distribute 
cocaine and conspiring to commit bribery after their weekend 
arrests which followed a sting operation 
marreros acquittal in the beating death of businessman arthur 
mcduffie sparked a riot that left 18 people dead and caused 80 
million in property damage in may 1980 
us attorney dexter lehtinen said marrero and villar had 
offered to protect a man who was posing as a smuggler bringing 
cocaine from the bahamas into an area near miami beach the man was 
actually working with government agents 
marrero and villar provided protection for this load of 
cocaine and in return demanded a fee of 300000 he said and 
marrero got 10 percent of the fee in cash 
according to an affidavit villar had certificates of deposit 
worth more than 300000 in a briefcase when he was arrested 
today we demonstrate no matter who you are or what you think 
you know if you deal in drugs you can be caught lehtinen told a 
news conference 
us magistrate william c turnoff ordered marrero and villar 
back to the federal metropolitan correctional center where they 
have been held without bond since saturday 
prosecutors asked that they be held as dangers to the community 
and because of the risk they might flee turnoff said he would make 
a decision on bonds for the two tuesday 
diane cossin executive assistant to lehtinen said conviction 
on the conspiracy and bribery charges would lead to automatic 
10year federal prison terms for the two men and possible life 
sentences she said other charges may be filed 
marrero was suspended from the metrodade force early in 1980 
after an investigation revealed that mcduffie had been beaten to 
death by police officers after a highway chase marrero the chief 
defendant in the case was charged with seconddegree murder 
