its fantastic its unreal he says its the thrill of a 
lifetime 
some bridge professionals are on the tournament trail virtually 
every week of the year but unlike sports such as tennis and golf 
80 percent to 90 percent of the tournament field is made up of 
ordinary bridge players of varying levels of expertise 
a trophy is awarded to the player who wins the most matchpoints 
each year neither hamman nor wolff has ever come close to winning 
it 
if you go after it it pretty well is a fulltime venture 
hamman says i play a lot of tournaments but not 40 a year 
which is pretty well what youd have to play it gets to be quite a 
grind going to boise idaho one week and then to butte mont 
and then to chicago 
still hamman concedes that if thousands of dollars in prize 
money were at stake that would be different he would be in 
the hunt 
some financial reward is available at every tournament some 
players pay professionals 400 to 500 a day to be their partners 
for various twosession events about seven hours of play 
for the first time in years jacoby traveled the tournament 
circuit last year playing sometimes with other pros and sometimes 
with paying clients he emerged as an easy victor in the 1988 
matchpoint chase 
jacoby says he made a determined run for the title because his 
father the late oswald jacoby won the title years ago the 
jacobys are the only fatherson combination to have won the trophy 
