<TEXT>
just a little over four years ago 
on march 15 1985 thousands of brazilians waving 
greenyellowandblue national flags rushed up the main ramp of 
the presidential palace in brasilia and cheered their nascent new 
republic 
the rightwing generals who had ruled for 21 years had stepped 
aside and hopes ran high brazil under civilian direction would 
bound forward toward the prosperous future so many had envisioned 
it hasnt happened 
and some brazilians often out of frustration say it was better 
when the generals ran things 
today under the centrist civilian presidency of jose sarney 
the 200 percent annual inflation left by the generals has soared to 
more than 1000 percent the cruzado currency has been devalued by 
a factor of 1 million 
public officials who were supposed to show how a responsible 
democracy could work in south america are involved in seemingly 
nonending scandals of payoffs kickbacks nepotism and misuse of 
government funds 
public services are deteriorating big cities are grimier than 
ever street crime is rising strikes often accompanied by 
violence disrupt daily life in one form or another 
brazilians with money and skills seek visas for portugal italy 
australia and canada or as a last resort to get into the united 
states and stay there illegally 
brazil is smothered by the biggest foreign debt in the third 
world 115 billion 
its only a matter of time before the armed forces will have 
to come back in a brazilian executive said recently on a luxury 
yacht sailing past sugar loaf mountain 
a taxi driver tells a passenger that all he has made for his 
long day negotiating rio de janeiros traffic is 15 cruzados 15 
at the official rate but in reality worth only 810 
why dont the generals just take over this he snarls 
still hes better off than most only 35 percent of brazilians 
make more than the minimum wage which is the equivalent of 64 a 
month 
indications are the taxi driver is not likely to get his wish 
the armed forces have shown no inclination to get involved again in 
politics military chiefs say repeatedly they will support the 
winner of the presidential election nov 15 no matter who it is 
and while some of the talk seems to favor a military return 
brazilians in general when it comes down to it hope it doesnt 
happen the dictatorships of 19301945 and 19641985 are still 
clearly remembered censorship secret arrests even torture 
in 1985 the new republic broadcast a slogan for government 
action everything for social progress 
but a study this year led by the sociologist helio jaguaribe 
and titled brazil reform or chaos concluded in no other 
country in the world not even india are social contrasts so 
shocking 
the research indicated that 41 percent of all brazilians live 
in a state of misery or strict poverty 
along rios stylish ipanema beach abandoned children in raggedy 
shorts sleep on the sidewalk outside 1million oceanview condos 
with garages protecting 75000 mercedes sports cars 
the amount of brazils total wealth held by the richest 1 
percent of the population about 13 percent equals that of the 
poorest 50 percent 
more than half of brazils tillable farmland is in the hands of 
2 percent of the countrys farmers 
although brazil has renowned universities and graduate programs 
just 9 percent of schoolage children make it through eighth grade 
the fundamental characteristic of brazilian society is its 
profound duality the jaguaribe study said on one side there 
is a modern industrial society on the other is a primitive 
society living at a subsistence level 
jair meneguelli is president of the militant central workers 
union which organized a partly successful twoday national protest 
strike in march 
brazils current crisis stems from a long history of 
corruption and a total lack of proper government priorities such as 
housing health and education he said 
if brazil does not change the future will be one of social 
convulsion 
</TEXT>
