<TEXT>
what brazil needs meneguelli said is the victory of a leftist 
reformer such as luis inacio lula da silva in novembers 
presidential balloting 
what brazil needs is time said sarney a 58yearold 
politician lawyer and poet 
he added in an interview with the associated press we have 
consolidated democratic institutions political groups formerly 
considered extremist now are playing politics by democratic rules 
we have not had any military uprisings or serious social 
upheavals 
one large problem is official graft charges of official 
corruption appear almost daily in the press officials including a 
cabinet minister routinely referred to as robber scarcely 
bother to refute them 
newsphotos purport to show official cars taking functionaries 
children to expensive private schools and their maids to the 
supermarket 
also underlying brazils ills is the enormous foreign debt 
sarney said that if creditors the main ones are big us banks 
simply do not write off part of what is owed democracy will be 
threatened and marxist alternatives will start looking attractive 
to the people 
most of the money was borrowed by the military government 
without objection from a rubberstamp congress but it did help 
brazil build some things necessary for progress airports and 
highways a modern telephone system a 10mile bridge across 
guanabara bay from rio to niteroi and the itaipu dam the worlds 
largest hydroelectric generator 
but a lot more money was wasted on projects that never panned 
out 
the borrowed money also created a veritable army of bigspending 
technocrats who in turn proliferated bureaucracies generally 
unaccountable to public scrutiny 
the ordinarily progovernment newspaper o globo of rio 
complained recently of gigantic gangs of lazy bureaucrats whose 
salaries and free spending affront millions of fellow citizens who 
because of ignorance must wait in lines of want and misery 
president sarney noted in the interview with the ap in brasilia 
that brazil in the last four years has paid 50 billion in debt 
interest alone money that would have allowed the implanatation 
of a gigantic program of national development 
shortly after taking office in 1985 sarney announced a sweeping 
program called brazil 2000 to improve living standards and 
reduce social inequality little or nothing has come of it 
sarney says brazil does not want confrontation with the foreign 
banks and governments and international organizations it owes money 
to 
but brazils next president might not be so moderate 
lula da silva a former strike organizer and leader of the 
marxistinspired workers party goes along with the view of 
president fidel castro of cuba brazil shouldnt pay any more 
leonel brizola a populist leftist firebrand of the 1960s who 
now calls himself a europeanstyle socialist says that while 
brazil shouldnt become an outright deadbeat the debt in its 
present form cannot be paid 
a private poll done in march and widely regarded as accurate 
indicated that brizola and da silva are the frontrunners at this 
point in the presidential race although the campaign is not 
officially under way 
finance minister mailson da nobrega told a group of foreign 
correspondents recently that if foreign creditors dont reduce the 
debt brazilians and other latin americans will turn to radicals 
and demagogues for future leadership 
but brazilians are fond of saying god is brazilian and not 
everyone is pessimistic 
brazil is further along the road to the upside scenario than 
many think said christopher r lund of the american chamber of 
commerce in sao paulo the nations financial center 
brazil is discovering more oil and gold and some voices now are 
being raised in favor of conserving rather than destroying the 
huge amazon rain forest 
and there still are brazilians who believe their country can 
make it through oldfashioned hard work 
brazils crisis has little to do with the political transition 
and much less with the foreign debt said sen roberto campos of 
the rightwing social democratic party who under the military 
regime was planning minister and ambassador to the united states 
campos solution 
deregulation more aggressive free enterprise unrestricted 
trade international market integration no more talk of marxism 
and labor militancy and an end to obsolete thinking and the lack 
of ideas for stimulating development 
