<TEXT>
ghost shrimp seldomseen crustaceans 
that have lived for eons beneath beach sand may provide fossilized 
clues that can help geologists locate valuable titanium deposits in 
the southeast 
igneous and metamorphic rocks that form the piedmont area and 
blue ridge mountains contain traces of titaniumrich heavy 
minerals as the rocks weather into sand and clay particles are 
carried down rivers and deposited along the coast waves and 
currents sort the particles by size and density depositing the 
heavy minerals on some parts of the beach 
the ghost shrimp that im studying appears to be almost 
restricted to the beaches and the heavy minerals are accumulating 
on the beaches said geologist gale bishop if we can identify 
burrows of that species in the past we should be able to find 
heavy mineral deposits 
heavy minerals like rutile and ilmenite contain titanium a 
strong light metal used by the space industry titanium oxide 
whitens paints and papers 
bishop of georgia southern college is pumping up ghost shrimp 
from beaches along the coast and recording their distribution 
shapes size and claw types the shrimp are seldom seen living out 
their lives deep in sandy burrows and feeding on organic debris 
bacteria and nutrients filtered from the water 
what we hope to see is the upper part of the burrow the 
vertical shaft which would indicate were near the sealevel of the 
past it might indicate heavy mineral deposits nearby bishop 
said the similarity of geological conditions in the 
carolinas georgia and northern florida should indicate that heavy 
mineral deposits could be found in any of these areas 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
james alleman has encountered more 
than the notinmybackyard syndrome in trying to deal with 
sewage sludge people who hear of his biobricks generally say 
not in my wall 
the environmental engineer worked with a maryland manufacturer 
to make bricks that have been used in two park shelters in 
washington dc and two sewage treatment plants for the 
washington suburban sanitary commission 
more recently hes discovered that even sludge laden with 
hazardous metals can be put into the claysludge mixture that is 
fired into bricks alleman has been unable to extract the metal 
except with the strongest acids 
we soaked them in an acid solution to simulate acid rain and 
we couldnt get the metals back out we had such a hard time we had 
to dissolve the bricks we had to use hydroflouric acid the 
strongest acid we have he said 
of course if builders have an aversion to bricks made with 
normal sludge theyre even less likely to use bricks made with 
hazardous metals like nickel arsenic cadmium chrome and lead 
no matter how safe they are 
theres a lot of inorganic sludge with hazardous wastes in it 
you cant put it on farmers lands because the crops would be 
contaminated with it alleman said those kinds of sludge are 
ideal candidates for bricks 
he estimated that american cities dispose of 6000 to 10000 
tons of sludge a day some bury it others burn it and a few still 
dump it in the ocean 
the key to allemans process is the brickmaking kiln which 
operates at 2000 degrees over two days to bake the 5050 mixture 
of clay and sludge into bricks in the process any organic matter 
in the sludge is burned away and any hazardous metals are fused 
permanently into the brick 
if i were a brick manufacturer i would find somebody to pay 
me to take sludge off their hands its easy you need very hose work is 
funded in part 
by the national science foundation 
