<TEXT>
every year thousands of tourists roam 
through north carolinas mountains on trails that range from short 
legstretchers along the blue ridge parkway to longdistance 
treks through the remote wilderness 
some end up lost others with injuries that run from sprains to 
broken legs a few die from falls exposure or overexertion 
here are some tips from experts on hiking in the mountains 
pick the right clothes wear hiking boots or a good pair of 
sneakers with deep tread heavy socks and loosefitting 
longlegged pants a tshirt is fine in moderate weather but carry 
a sweater or wind breaker that can be tied around the waist and 
take a hat even if its just a baseball cap add more clothing as 
the weather becomes more extreme 
wearing a pair of thin nylon socks with hiking boots is about 
like going barefoot said jeff wahoo stanley owner of wahoos 
outdoor adventures in boone weve found that some of the best 
pants for hiking are just ordinary sweatpants the kind with a 
drawstring waist they protect your legs but theyre comfortable 
and warm 
carry a minimum amount of equipment anyone going into the 
woods even on a short hike should carry a pocket knife a 
cigarette lighter water and a few firstaid supplies a small 
daypack can hold lunches and enough supplies for several people 
choose the right trail steep rugged trails might be fine for 
an experienced 30yearold hiker but a 6yearold or novice hiker 
doesnt need that much of a challenge check with outfitters or 
other local experts about available trails their degree of 
difficulty and hazards 
make sure someone knows where you are always tell someone 
what trail you intend to take and your estimated return time 
never hike alone the worst thing you can do is go out by 
yourself because you never know what can happen said tom collins 
of the watauga county emergency management office you get bitten 
by a snake turn an ankle or take a fall and youre just out there 
on your own until somebody happens to come across you 
do not leave the trail heavy foliage in the mountains 
sometimes hides sheer drops and taking a shortcut on a trail that 
winds back and forth on a mountainside can lead to erosion and 
other ecological damage 
dont panic if you lose your way stop and think before 
taking action following a stream downstream will eventually lead 
to a road or a place where you can get help if darkness is 
falling stay where you are for the night wandering around in the 
darkness can lead to a fall wait for daylight and make your way 
back to the trail 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

