washington taiwans exportimport bank announced plans monday 
to provide loans to american companies to help encourage american 
exports and reduce the huge us trade deficit with the island 
the loans are part of the taiwan governments continuing 
campaign to persuade taiwanese firms to buy american said kw 
kung executive vice president of the exportimport bank of the 
republic of china on taiwan 
kung said the bank has 200 million to lend to american 
companies to help them export machinery and other goods and 
services to taiwan against deferred payment from purchasers 
kung plans to take his loan message to eight us cities 
stretching from boston and new york to seattle and los angeles 
the unique effort to promote another countrys exports stemmed 
from concern in taiwan that it would be targeted under new us 
trade laws directed against countries who persistently sell more to 
the united states than they buy 
sheu kesheng economic director of taiwans washington mission 
said that within four years the surplus should be largely 
eliminated but to reduce it to zero is very difficult 
the us trade deficit with taiwan dropped from 18 to 141 
billion from 1987 to 1988 and is expected to narrow by at least 10 
percent a year he said sheu said his governments own statistics 
showed the taiwan surplus dropped from 16 billion to 104 billion 
the past year 
us trade with taiwan started registering deficits in the early 
1970s and since then the island has sent 15 buy american 
purchasing missions to the united states reduced import tariffs 16 
times and more recently appreciated its currency 49 percent 
against the us dollar sheu said 
another round of tariff reductions will be announcd in a few 
weeks and plans call for reducing taiwans average tariff at 55 
percent now comparable to that of the united states to 35 percent 
within four years he added 
kung said us exporters hoping to use taiwan exportimport bank 
credit may contact any of about 40 us major and regional banks 
authorized to borrow from his bank at 655 percent annual interest 
making for a relending rate to the exporter of approximately 83 
percent 
